 way. Their difficult paths, complex choices, and triumphs are revealed through the experiences of the first black woman professor in educational administration, a fight to the death for tenure, a genteel southerner's confrontation with the aloof North, and a brash northerner's survival of the cultural complexities of the South. These stories speak not simply to women, but to all trailblazers in the workplace, and to those still facing discrimination and relegated to outsider status.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Educational Administration. 4aEducation : Higher Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 7aEDUCATION / Administration / General.2bisacsh1 aBauch, Patricia A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBueschel, Ellen V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCambron-McCabe, Nelda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardiner, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Barbara L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeeler, Carolyn M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalen, Betty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCarthy, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMertz, Norma T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMertz, Norma T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPounder, Diana G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrestine, Nona A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRusch, Edith A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShort, Paul